# Multi-tenancy

This project ships with **`django-tenants`** wired in: each tenant gets a
native PostgreSQL schema, isolated from every other tenant at the database
layer.

## Mental model

```
                в”Ңв”Җ public schema в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ
                в”Ӯ  apps.tenants  (Tenant, Domain)   в”Ӯ
                в”Ӯ  apps.users   (User вҖ” global)     в”Ӯ
                в”Ӯ  apps.flags                       в”Ӯ
                в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ
                          в–І hostname lookup
        в”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”јв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ
        в–ј                 в–ј                     в–ј
  acme schema       widgetco schema       beta-corp schema
  в”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ      в”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ        в”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ
  в”Ӯ TENANT_  в”Ӯ      в”Ӯ TENANT_    в”Ӯ        в”Ӯ TENANT_      в”Ӯ
  в”Ӯ APPS вҖҰ   в”Ӯ      в”Ӯ APPS вҖҰ     в”Ӯ        в”Ӯ APPS вҖҰ       в”Ӯ
  в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ      в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ        в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ
```

- `SHARED_APPS` (the `public` schema): `tenants`, `users`, flags, admin вҖ”
  things every tenant uses but the data is global.
- `TENANT_APPS` (per-schema): your business models. Same migrations, separate
  data, zero cross-tenant leakage at the DB level.

## Bootstrap

First deploy (or `docker compose up --build` for the first time):

```bash
# Apply migrations to the public schema (SHARED_APPS).
uv run python manage.py migrate_schemas --shared

# Ensure the public Tenant + Domain row exist (idempotent).
uv run python manage.py bootstrap_public_tenant

# Create your first paying tenant.
uv run python manage.py create_tenant \
    --schema=acme --name="Acme Inc" \
    --paid-until=2027-01-01 \
    --domain-domain=acme.{{ cookiecutter.domain_name }} \
    --domain-is_primary=true
```

The new tenant's schema is created automatically (`auto_create_schema=True`
on the Tenant model) and all `TENANT_APPS` migrations run against it.

## Routing

`django_tenants.middleware.main.TenantMainMiddleware` is the first middleware.
On every request:

1. It reads `request.get_host()` (e.g. `acme.{{ cookiecutter.domain_name }}`).
2. Looks up `Domain.objects.get(domain=...)`.
3. Sets `connection.set_schema(tenant.schema_name)` вҶ’ every ORM query runs
   against the tenant's schema for the rest of the request.

## Adding a tenant model

Put it in `TENANT_APPS`. Migrations look identical to a single-tenant app вҖ”
django-tenants handles schema scoping automatically:

```python
# apps/projects/models.py
class Project(models.Model):
    name = models.CharField(max_length=200)
    # No tenant_id column needed вҖ” schema isolation handles it.
```

```bash
uv run python manage.py makemigrations projects
uv run python manage.py migrate_schemas         # applies to every tenant
```

## What stays in the public schema

- `apps.tenants` вҖ” Tenant + Domain (must be public; routing depends on it)
- `apps.users` вҖ” by default users are global, so they can switch tenants
  (set up via UserTenantPermissions in the future if you want per-tenant
  invitations). Move to `TENANT_APPS` if your users live inside one tenant.
- `django.contrib.admin`, `django.contrib.contenttypes`,
  `django.contrib.sessions`, `django.contrib.auth` вҖ” public.
- `django-waffle` flags if you ship the feature-flags add-on вҖ” flags are
  global, per-tenant flag overrides live in `Switch.users` via UserTenantPermission.

## Tenant routing in dev

For local development without DNS:

```
# /etc/hosts
127.0.0.1   {{ cookiecutter.domain_name }}
127.0.0.1   acme.{{ cookiecutter.domain_name }}
127.0.0.1   widgetco.{{ cookiecutter.domain_name }}
```

Then `http://acme.{{ cookiecutter.domain_name }}:8000/` routes to the acme schema.

## Operational gotchas

- **Backup**: `pg_dump --schema=acme` backs up one tenant. `pg_dumpall` for all.
- **Migrations**: `migrate_schemas` (the django-tenants command), NOT plain
  `migrate`. The latter only touches the public schema.
- **Async tasks**: Celery workers must call `tenant_context(tenant)` before
  touching tenant data. `django-tenants-celery-beat` adds per-tenant
  scheduling if you need it.
- **Test DB**: tests use `django_tenants.test.TenantTestCase`; the test
  runner creates a fresh schema per test class. Slower than vanilla pytest
  but isolation is exact.
